<h2>Data Grid</h2>
<p>The interactive twin of the <a href="/blocks/data-table/">Data Table block</a> — the same tabular data, the <em>other</em> WAI-ARIA APG pattern. It renders a native <code>&lt;table <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/">role="grid"</a>&gt;</code> of <code>role="row"</code> / <code>role="columnheader"</code> / <code>role="gridcell"</code> cells with <strong>cell-level keyboard navigation</strong> over a <strong>roving tabindex</strong>: exactly one cell is <code>tabindex="0"</code> (the active cell), every other is <code>-1</code>, and a keystroke roves the <code>0</code> to the next cell. It is the concrete consumer of the <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">Focus Delegation</a> intent — strategy <code>roving</code>, orientation <code>both</code>. Where Data Table is <em>read-and-reorder</em> (<code>role="table"</code> + <code>aria-sort</code>), Data Grid is <em>navigate-the-cells</em> (<code>role="grid"</code> + roving focus); APG documents these as separate patterns, so they are <strong>parallel blocks, not one upgraded in place</strong> (decision carried from <a href="/backlog/115-data-table-interactivity-announcements/">#115</a>).</p>

<p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
  <strong>Terminology:</strong> See <a href="/semantics/">Semantics &amp; Glossary</a> for terms like
  <a href="/semantics/#term-roving-tabindex">roving tabindex</a> and
  <a href="/semantics/#term-aria-activedescendant">aria-activedescendant</a>, plus the
  <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">Focus Delegation intent</a> for the focus model this realizes.
</p>

