<h3>Architecture</h3>
<p>Data Grid is a <strong>Module</strong> that composes <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">Focus Delegation</a>; it owns only the grid projection and the cell-navigation model, delegating the data operations to its read-only twin:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>DataGridModule</strong>: renders the row set as the <code>role="grid"</code> structure (<code>renderDataGrid</code>) with the roving tabindex seeded at the origin (the top-left header cell).</li>
  <li><strong>DataGridBehavior</strong> (<code>grid:cell-navigation</code>): attaches to the grid, reads the pure movement engine (<code>nextCellPosition</code>) on each <code>keydown</code>, roves the <code>tabindex="0"</code> to the new cell (<code>setActiveCell</code>), moves real DOM focus there, and <strong>scrolls the active cell into view</strong> on each move (required once rows are windowed). It reads dimensions from the live DOM — so it survives a grid that grows/shrinks — clamps at the edges by default, and layers an opt-in <code>wrap</code> (<code>grid:cell-navigation="wrap"</code>) over the clamping engine. It emits <code>grid-cell-change</code> (<code>{ from, to }</code>) on every committed move and click-focuses a clicked cell.</li>
  <li><strong>DataGridEditBehavior</strong> (<code>grid:cell-edit</code>): the optional <a href="#editable-cells">editable sub-pattern</a> layered on the same grid — see below. It reads the pure mode engine (<code>editAction</code>) and stays fully decoupled from the navigation behavior (it never touches the roving tabindex or the movement engine).</li>
  <li><a href="/blocks/data-table/">Data Table</a> owns <code>filter</code> / <code>sort</code> / <code>group</code>; <a href="/intents/windowed-collection/">Windowed Collection</a> owns which rows are realized in the DOM; <a href="/intents/selection/">Selection</a> is an orthogonal co-resident axis. <strong>Compose, never merge.</strong></li>
</ul>

<h3>The keyboard model</h3>
<p>One tab stop, arrows within — the APG composite-widget invariant. The column-header row is itself navigable, so positions range over <code>1 (header) + dataRows</code> rows:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Arrow keys</strong> move focus one cell along each axis (orientation <code>both</code>), <strong>clamping</strong> at the edges — this grid does not wrap.</li>
  <li><strong>Home / End</strong> jump to the first / last cell of the current row.</li>
  <li><strong>Ctrl+Home / Ctrl+End</strong> jump to the grid corners — the first cell of the first row / the last cell of the last row (<kbd>⌘</kbd> is treated the same on macOS).</li>
  <li><strong>PageUp / PageDown</strong> move up / down by <code>pageSize</code> rows (default 5), clamping.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="editable-cells">Editable cells — the APG editable sub-pattern</h3>
<p>APG documents an <strong>editable</strong> mode the navigation grid <em>composes</em> with: a focused data cell can drop into an editor while the grid's cell navigation is suspended. This ships as a <strong>separate, composable behavior</strong> — <code>grid:cell-edit</code> (<code>DataGridEditBehavior</code>) — on the <em>same</em> block, not a new parallel block and not an option folded into the navigation behavior. The two attributes coexist on one element: <code>&lt;table role="grid" grid:cell-navigation grid:cell-edit&gt;</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Why a separate behavior, not a parallel block (cf. Data Table vs Data Grid).</strong> Data Table and Data Grid are <em>different APG patterns</em> (<code>role="table"</code> + <code>aria-sort</code> vs <code>role="grid"</code> + roving focus), so they are parallel blocks. Editing is the <em>same</em> APG grid pattern with an editing <strong>mode</strong> on top — APG documents it as the editable sub-pattern <em>of</em> the grid. Folding it into the navigation behavior would thicken the navigation contract with an orthogonal concern, so it is a distinct attribute that layers cleanly and leaves <code>grid:cell-navigation</code> untouched (<em>composition over monolith</em>).</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Enter / F2</strong> on a focused data cell open an editor seeded with the cell value; a column header never edits (it is a label), and neither does an <strong><code>aria-readonly="true"</code></strong> cell — editability is declared in the DOM and announced to assistive tech. A cell's own <code>aria-readonly</code> wins (<code>"false"</code> is an explicit editable override); otherwise the grid's <code>aria-readonly="true"</code> makes every cell read-only by default.</li>
  <li><strong>Typed editors</strong> (per column, declared on the cell): <code>data-editor="text"</code> (default) / <code>"number"</code> / <code>"date"</code> open the native input of that type; <code>"select"</code> opens a <code>&lt;select&gt;</code> of <code>data-editor-options</code> (comma-separated). Native validation attributes (<code>required</code>, <code>min</code>, <code>max</code>) pass through, so an <strong>invalid value does not commit</strong>: pressing Enter on it keeps the editor open (marked <code>aria-invalid</code>) and emits <code>grid-cell-edit-invalid</code>; a host can also <code>reject()</code> a value on the commit event for custom rules. (Blur on an invalid value cancels rather than trapping focus.)</li>
  <li><strong>Arrows edit the field, not the grid:</strong> while editing, arrow keys move the caret <em>within</em> the field and the grid does not navigate. The mechanism is fully decoupled — the editor's own <code>keydown</code> listener <code>stopPropagation()</code>s, so the navigation behavior's grid-level listener never sees the key; caret movement is the input's default action, unaffected by <code>stopPropagation</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Escape</strong> cancels and restores the prior value; <strong>Enter</strong> commits and returns focus to the cell; blur (clicking away) commits.</li>
  <li><strong>Commit strategy is a named seam, not this block's concern:</strong> commit emits a <em>cancelable</em> <code>grid-cell-edit-commit</code> (<code>{ position, value, previousValue, reject() }</code>). The reference default writes the value in-place; a host <code>preventDefault()</code>s to own the write (optimistic / server) and the editor restores the previous value as the pending state, or <code>reject()</code>s to mark the value invalid and keep editing. <code>grid-cell-edit-start</code>, <code>grid-cell-edit-cancel</code>, and <code>grid-cell-edit-invalid</code> round out the observable mode model. The block owns the <strong>mode</strong>; the app owns the <strong>strategy</strong>.</li>
</ul>
<p>The mode model is CI-guarded exactly as the navigation contract is: a pure engine (<code>editAction</code>), a sibling audit (<code>auditEditableGrid</code>), and shared fixtures drive both the <a href="/demos/data-grid-demo.html">playground</a>'s editable cards and the conformance suite.</p>

<h3>Accessibility contract (verified)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>A native <code>&lt;table role="grid"&gt;</code>; rows are <code>role="row"</code>, header cells <code>role="columnheader"</code>, data cells <code>role="gridcell"</code>; the grid declares <code>aria-rowcount</code> / <code>aria-colcount</code> over the full extent (header included).</li>
  <li><strong>Roving tabindex:</strong> exactly one cell carries <code>tabindex="0"</code> — the active cell — and every other cell is <code>tabindex="-1"</code>; a keystroke recomputes the active cell and the <code>0</code> roves to it.</li>
  <li><strong>Live interactivity (wired):</strong> the <a href="/demos/data-grid-demo.html">playground</a>'s live grid is driven by the real <code>grid:cell-navigation</code> behavior — click in and the arrow / Home / End / Ctrl+corner / Page keys move real DOM focus cell to cell; each move re-runs the same audit CI asserts, so the contract badge stays honest. The movement engine, the active-cell projection, and the attribute behavior are the one shared source the demo and the conformance suite both drive.</li>
  <li><strong>Clamp, not wrap</strong> is the default; wrapping is a <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">Focus Delegation</a> <code>wrap</code> concern the behavior layers on opt-in (<code>grid:cell-navigation="wrap"</code>) over the clamping engine, off by default.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Composition &amp; seam decisions</h3>
<p>The Data Grid does <em>not</em> re-implement focus management — it realizes Focus Delegation's <code>roving</code> strategy over two axes, and the <strong>movement engine</strong> (<code>nextCellPosition</code>) is the verifiable seam. It is a parallel block to the <a href="/blocks/data-table/">Data Table</a>, not a sortable table upgraded in place: the two compose onto the same collection when both reordering and cell traversal are wanted. <a href="#editable-cells">Editable cells</a> are the same APG grid pattern with an editing mode, so they ship as a <em>composable behavior</em> on this block (<code>grid:cell-edit</code>) rather than a parallel block; two-dimensional selection and virtualized rows remain concrete strategies that register against these seams without changing the contract.</p>

<h3>HTML Usage</h3>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!-- Data grid: one cell is the roving tabindex=0; arrows move focus cell to cell.
     Add grid:cell-edit for the editable sub-pattern (Enter/F2 to edit, Esc/Enter to cancel/commit). --&gt;
&lt;table role="grid" grid:cell-navigation grid:cell-edit aria-rowcount="3" aria-colcount="2"&gt;
  &lt;thead&gt;
    &lt;tr role="row" aria-rowindex="1"&gt;
      &lt;th role="columnheader" tabindex="0"  aria-colindex="1"&gt;Name&lt;/th&gt;
      &lt;th role="columnheader" tabindex="-1" aria-colindex="2"&gt;Team&lt;/th&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
  &lt;/thead&gt;
  &lt;tbody&gt;
    &lt;tr role="row" aria-rowindex="2"&gt;
      &lt;td role="gridcell" tabindex="-1" aria-colindex="1"&gt;Aaron&lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;td role="gridcell" tabindex="-1" aria-colindex="2"&gt;Engineering&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
  &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<h3>Interface (contracts only)</h3>
<p>Web Everything defines the contract; concrete strategy implementations (virtualized rows, editable cells, server paging, two-dimensional selection) live in <strong>Frontier UI</strong> and register against these seams without changing the contract.</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-typescript">interface GridColumn { field: string; label: string; }

interface CellPosition { row: number; col: number; }  // row 0 = the header row

interface DataGridContract {
  columns: GridColumn[];
  pageSize?: number;   // rows per PageUp/PageDown; default 5
  caption?: string;
}

// The pure movement engine — the seam the demo and CI both drive.
// Arrows clamp; Home/End to row ends; Ctrl+Home/End to grid corners; PageUp/Down by pageSize.
function nextCellPosition(
  pos: CellPosition,
  key: { key: string; ctrlKey?: boolean; metaKey?: boolean },
  dims: { rows: number; cols: number },   // rows INCLUDES the header row
  pageSize?: number,
): CellPosition;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<h3>Status &amp; scope</h3>
<p><code>status: draft</code> — the contract, the APG Data Grid / roving-tabindex design, the
<a href="#editable-cells">editable sub-pattern</a> mode model (<code>grid:cell-edit</code>), and a fixture-driven
<a href="/demos/data-grid-demo.html">conformance demo</a> ship here; remaining concrete strategies
(virtualization, server paging, cell selection) and the <em>commit strategy</em> behind editing
(optimistic / server writes) are deferred to Frontier UI. The <code>filter</code> /
<code>sort</code> / <code>group</code> operations are the separate <a href="/blocks/data-table/">Data Table
block</a>; this block owns only cell navigation and composes the data-operations block on the same
collection when both are wanted.</p>
